Chicken Cigar Rolls  with our Ramadan partner @shangrilapakistan | Easy and Delicious Recipe

Chicken Cigars

Ingredients for Chicken Mixture:
Boneless chicken (cubes) 250 g
Eggs 1
Red chili powder: Half tbsp
Ginger garlic paste: Half tbsp
Paprika powder: Half tbsp
Salt : Half tsp
Cumin powder: Half tbsp
Turmeric powder :1/4 tsp
Vinegar : Half tbsp

Ingredients for Flour Mixture:
All-purpose flour 1/4  cup
Water quarter cup

Ingredients for Assembling:
Roll patti as required
Flour mixture as required
Chicken mixture as required
Oil (for frying) as required

Directions:
1. In a chopper add chicken, eggs, red chili powder, ginger and garlic paste, lemon juice, paprika powder, salt, cumin powder, and turmeric powder. Chop it well into mince.
2. In a bowl add flour and water and make a slurry.
3. Now take a roll patti, Brush flour mixture on one side of the roll patti.  Now mixture add in frosting bag. . 
4.. Make all Chicken cigars like that .
Note: Can be frozen in airtight bag for up to 1 month
5. Fry them until they get crispy and golden brown.
6. Your Chicken Cigars are ready.
Prep time: 25-30 mins.

🥀And serve with  shangrila sauces.

Product review: @gadgetguru_69  they've sent me Apple Air Pods Pro 

What I like: 
- fit 
- good sound quality
- noise reduction and transparency modes
- integration with accessibility functions. I can use an audio gram app to produce a hearing test (it registered less loss than my professional test) and Air Pods Pro adapt the sound to my hearing loss profile. Alternatively, it has a menu process to tune the sound to your preference/ hearing. As it turns out, I like the menu version better since the 3rd party app understated my hearing loss. 
- Bluetooth range better than other BT pods I’ve used
- integrates with the hearing protection sound meter function on my Apple Watch. I know how many dB of sound the pods make and can set limits to protect from further loss (in case I get excited and turn it up). The noise reduction feature means I find that I typically am comfortable listening at only about 60-65 dB and don’t feel like I’m missing out on any dynamics or nuance. 
- water resistant enough to not worry about. 

What I don’t like:
- I can’t just enter my audio gram numbers direct from my hearing test to manually fine tune. 

What I love:
- listening to Rach 2, second movement the way I remember it in the hot tub under the stars. 

Highly recommended.
